\section{Unified Telegraph Dynamics (Stable, Causal)}

\subsection{Dimensionless setting and notation}
We adopt the global, dimensionless normalization introduced earlier:
choose $(\ell_0,t_0,\Psi_0)$ and report all equations in hats thereafter
(hats omitted for readability). A dimensionless Planck factor $\hat\hbar$
may be absorbed into energy prefactors.%
{\small \,:contentReference[oaicite:0]{index=0}}

\paragraph{Fourier--Laplace convention.}
Time derivatives map to $s\in\mathbb C$ and Laplacian to $-|k|^2$
under $(\partial_t,\nabla^2)\mapsto(s,-|k|^2)$; $\tau>0$ and $c>0$
denote the (dimensionless) relaxation time and finite propagation speed.%
{\small \,:contentReference[oaicite:1]{index=1}}

\subsection{Telegraph-stable core and dispersion}
The unified (dimensionless) telegraph core for the coherence field $\Psi$ is
\begin{equation}
\tau\,\partial_t^2\Psi+\partial_t\Psi - c^2\nabla^2\Psi
\;=\; \mathcal{F}(\Psi;\,a,\rho,J_{\!fb}) \;+\; \Gamma(\Psi_q,\varphi),
\label{eq:telegraph_core}
\end{equation}
where the right-hand side collects divergence of fluxes and feedback currents
(and may include weakly nonlinear source terms), together with causal stochastic
forcing $\Gamma$.%
{\small \,:contentReference[oaicite:2]{index=2}}

\paragraph{Dispersion and stability window.}
In the homogeneous limit of \eqref{eq:telegraph_core}, the dispersion relation is
\begin{equation}
\tau s^2+s+c^2|k|^2=0
\quad\Longrightarrow\quad
s(k)=\frac{-1\pm\sqrt{1-4\tau c^2|k|^2}}{2\tau}.
\label{eq:dispersion}
\end{equation}
For $4\tau c^2|k|^2>1$ (underdamped), $\Re s=-\tfrac{1}{2\tau}$; otherwise
$\,s\in\mathbb R_{<0}$ (over/critical damping). In all cases $\Re s<0$, ensuring
finite-rate decay and causality.%
{\small \,:contentReference[oaicite:3]{index=3}\,:contentReference[oaicite:4]{index=4}}

\subsection{Stochastic assumptions (causality)}
All stochastic sources are zero-mean and causal, with white-noise correlations
of the form
\[
\langle \Gamma(\cdot)\rangle=0,\qquad
\langle \xi(t)\rangle=0,\qquad
\langle \xi(t)\,\xi(t')\rangle=2D\,\delta(t-t'),\quad D\ge0.
\]
These conventions keep the PDE layer compatible with the residual-space
Lyapunov dissipation.%
{\small \,:contentReference[oaicite:5]{index=5}\,:contentReference[oaicite:6]{index=6}}

\subsection{Boundary conditions and well-posedness}
To guarantee existence/uniqueness for the telegraph core (and the coupled phase
equation used later), impose standard BCs on a bounded domain $\Omega$ or a
torus $\mathbb T^d$:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Periodic} on $\mathbb T^d$;
\item \textbf{Homogeneous Neumann} $\partial_n\Psi=0$ on $\partial\Omega$;
\item \textbf{Dirichlet} $\Psi=\Psi_{\mathrm{bc}}$ on $\partial\Omega$ with compatible initial data.
\end{itemize}
Assume coefficients are bounded/measurable and the diffusion modulus is uniformly
positive to retain parabolic/hyperbolic coercivity.%
{\small \,:contentReference[oaicite:7]{index=7}}

\subsection{Minimal energy estimate (compatibility with residual dissipation)}
Define the field energy density (one convenient choice)
\[
\mathcal E(\Psi):=\tfrac12\,|\partial_t\Psi|^2+\tfrac{c^2}{2}\,|\nabla\Psi|^2,
\]
and $E(t)=\int_\Omega \mathcal E(\Psi)\,dx$. For the homogeneous core of
\eqref{eq:telegraph_core} without stochastic/source terms, standard multipliers
yield $\dot E\le 0$; the decay rate is controlled by the dispersion
\eqref{eq:dispersion}. This is consistent with the residual-space Lyapunov law
$\dot V\le0$ used in Chapters~4--5.%
{\small \,:contentReference[oaicite:8]{index=8}\,:contentReference[oaicite:9]{index=9}}

\subsection{Operator bridge from the local algebra}
The telegraph operator arises naturally from the symbolic substitution layer
that maps $(\omega,\kappa)\mapsto(i\partial_t,-\nabla^2)$ applied to the
dimensionless near-one algebra of Chapter~4; after normalization (this section),
the resulting PDE inherits scale invariance and the stability window.%
{\small \,:contentReference[oaicite:10]{index=10}}

\paragraph{Takeaway.}
Equations \eqref{eq:telegraph_core}--\eqref{eq:dispersion} provide a
dimensionless, symmetry-consistent, and provably \emph{stable} telegraph layer
for $\Psi$, compatible with causal noise, standard boundary conditions, and the
Lyapunov dissipation recorded at the residual level.
