\section{Symmetry Breaking, Constraints, and Gauge Choices}

\subsection{Symmetry landscape (local-only)}
We recall the local scale map (Chs.~2--4)
\[
(\kappa,\omega,b,\rho)\ \mapsto\ (\lambda^2\kappa,\ \lambda\omega,\ \lambda b,\ \lambda^{-1}\rho),\qquad \lambda>0,
\]
under which the invariants $(\Pi_1,\Pi_2,\Pi_3)$ and the seed log-linearization
are preserved. At the field level, the telegraph core (Chs.~6--7) is invariant
under additive time shifts and, in the presence of a phase variable,
under local phase reparameterizations $\varphi\mapsto\varphi+\phi_0$ when
sources depend only on phase differences. These symmetries are \emph{local-only}
(no nonlocal kernels or global memory).

\subsection{Constraints vs.\ gauges: definitions}
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Constraints} restrict feasible states (physical or calibration): 
box bounds on $\varepsilon$, equality relations among components, positivity of
weights $W$, etc. They alter the feasible set and can change the optimizer.
\item \textbf{Gauges} remove redundancies without changing physical predictions:
reference phase $\theta(\Psi)$, baseline offsets that cancel in observables,
or the choice of anchor units (rad/s vs.\ Hz). Fixing a gauge selects a
representative from an equivalence class.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Residual layer with constraints (projection and multipliers)}
Given $r(\varepsilon)=G\varepsilon-\delta$ and weight $W\succeq0$ (Chs.~13--15),
constrained estimation solves
\begin{equation}
\min_{\varepsilon}\ \tfrac12\,\|r(\varepsilon)\|_W^2
\quad\text{s.t.}\quad
A_{\mathrm{eq}}\varepsilon=b_{\mathrm{eq}},\qquad \ell\le \varepsilon\le u.
\label{eq:residual_constrained}
\end{equation}
Two portable strategies:
\paragraph{(i) Projected metric.}
Let $\Pi_{\mathcal C}$ be the projection onto the box $[\ell,u]$; use
\[
\varepsilon^{k+1}=\Pi_{\mathcal C}\big(\varepsilon^k-\eta_k\,\Lambda_k\,G^\top W(G\varepsilon^k-\delta)\big)
\]
with $\Lambda_k\succeq0$ (Ch.~14). Equality constraints are enforced by projecting
the direction onto the nullspace of $A_{\mathrm{eq}}$.

\paragraph{(ii) Lagrange multipliers (KKT).}
Solve the saddle system for the linearized step $p$:
\[
\begin{bmatrix}
G^\top W G & A_{\mathrm{eq}}^\top\\
A_{\mathrm{eq}} & 0
\end{bmatrix}
\begin{bmatrix}
p\\ \lambda
\end{bmatrix}
=
-\begin{bmatrix}
G^\top W (G\varepsilon-\delta)\\
A_{\mathrm{eq}}\varepsilon-b_{\mathrm{eq}}
\end{bmatrix},
\]
then update $\varepsilon\leftarrow \Pi_{[\ell,u]}(\varepsilon+p)$. Both methods
are dimensionless and local-only.

\subsection{Gauge fixing in the phase/field layer}
The phase coupling (Ch.~8) uses a reference $\theta(\Psi)$ that enters only via
differences $\varphi-\theta(\Psi)$. To avoid drift in a neutrally stable phase
direction, choose a \emph{local gauge}:
\[
\theta(\Psi)=\arg(\Psi),\quad\text{or}\quad 
\theta(\Psi)=\mathcal G(\Psi)\ \text{with}\ \mathcal G\ \text{local, Lipschitz}.
\]
Gauge changes $\theta\mapsto \theta+\phi_0$ induce $\varphi\mapsto \varphi+\phi_0$
with no change to physical observables or the Energy--Coherence budget.
For the telegraph PDE, additive offsets in $\Psi$ are fixed by boundary/mean
conditions (periodic mean-zero or Dirichlet anchoring).

\subsection{Symmetry breaking: when and why}
Breaking a symmetry is legitimate when it:
(i) removes degeneracy that harms identifiability or numerical stability,
(ii) is realized by a gauge choice that leaves observables invariant, or
(iii) encodes a physical constraint (e.g., positivity or pinned boundary data).
Examples:
\begin{itemize}
\item \textbf{Phase pinning:} fix $\theta(\Psi)$ at a point or region to kill
global phase drift; $\rho_{\mathrm{lock}},\chi_{\mathrm{lock}}$ remain well-defined.
\item \textbf{Unit anchor:} adopt rad/s (Option A) globally; Hz appears only in
figures via $f_0=\Omega_0/(2\pi)$.
\item \textbf{Mean removal:} enforce $\int_\Omega \Psi\,dx=0$ (periodic), which
is a harmless gauge for dynamics that depend on gradients and time derivatives.
\end{itemize}

\subsection{Compatibility with Energy--Coherence and stability}
Any constraint or gauge must preserve the telegraph window and the energy law.
For the constrained residual problem, ensure the projected/augmented steps
remain descent directions in the metric induced by $W$:
\[
V(\varepsilon^{k+1})\le V(\varepsilon^k)\quad\text{with}\quad
V=\tfrac12\|G\varepsilon-\delta\|_W^2.
\]
For the field, gauge operations are algebraic and local; they do not alter
the dissipative terms (Ch.~10) nor the dispersion (Ch.~6).

\subsection{Local gauge for measurement maps (non-circular)}
If a measurement map admits an arbitrary baseline (e.g., a log-gain or offset),
fix it \emph{after} defining $\delta=\mathcal M(\mathcal O[\Psi])+\eta$ (Ch.~10),
never before. This prevents circular definitions linking $\delta$ to $\varepsilon$.
All calibrations (e.g., $W_0$) are reported explicitly and locally.

\subsection{Inequality constraints on phase and field}
Typical local constraints:
\[
|\varphi|\le \pi,\qquad \Psi_{\min}\le \Psi \le \Psi_{\max},\qquad
0\le J(\Psi)\le J_{\max}.
\]
Enforce them by projection in time-stepping (Ch.~12) or by proximal penalties:
\[
\min_{\Psi}\ \mathcal J(\Psi)
:= E_{\text{coh}}(\Psi) + \iota_{[\Psi_{\min},\Psi_{\max}]}(\Psi),
\]
where $\iota$ is the indicator of the feasible interval; implicit steps with
projection preserve the discrete energy decrease.

\subsection{Falsifiable checks (governance-compliant)}
\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Gauge invariance:} run two simulations differing only by a constant
phase shift in $\theta$; show identical $(E_{\text{coh}},\rho_{\mathrm{lock}},\chi_{\mathrm{lock}})$
trajectories (up to the trivial shift).
\item \textbf{Constraint descent:} under box/equality constraints, verify monotone
decrease of $V$ for accepted steps; ablate projections to demonstrate failure.
\item \textbf{Mean removal neutrality:} with/without mean-zero gauge for periodic
BC, confirm identical dispersion and energy decay (differences appear only as a
constant offset).
\end{enumerate}

\subsection{Implementation notes (dimensionless)}
\begin{itemize}
\item Use rad/s anchors (Option A) throughout; do not mix Hz into algebra.
\item Prefer QR-based KKT solves for constrained WLS (avoid squaring the
condition number).
\item In time-stepping, apply projection after each implicit or IMEX step and
recompute the discrete energy to enforce the Energy--Coherence check.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Takeaway.}
Constraints change feasible sets; gauges remove redundancy. Both can be handled
locally—with projections, KKT systems, and phase pinning—without violating
telegraph stability, Energy--Coherence monotonicity, or non-circularity of the
measurement loop. The result is a symmetry-aware, dimensionless, K-free practice
for robust inference and evolution across the stack.
